The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Sunday, July 18, 2004 				 AllBank to set up branch in Hong Kong
 A STAFF REPORTER				 	 Singh: Going places																								Calcutta, July 17: Allahabad Bank is all set to launch its first foreign branch in Hong Kong. The bank has already approached the Reserve Bank of India and authorities in Hong Kong for clearance.																								The branch will mark the banks entry into the overseas market, said chairman and managing director O. N. Singh. It is a major step towards attaining the high growth rate the bank has set out to achieve.																								The bank has posted a 102.5 per cent rise in first-quarter net profit at Rs 137.65 crore compared with Rs 67.97 crore in the previous corresponding period. Operating profit rose 66.41 per cent in the reporting quarter.																								Total income rose to Rs 987.02 crore from Rs 767.91 crore in April-June 2003.																								The banks business has crossed the Rs 50,000-crore-mark to touch Rs 51,675 crore as on June 30, 2004. On a year-on-year basis, the business has increased 31.2 per cent against a growth of 14.70 per cent in the corresponding period last year.																								Net non-performing assets (NPA) during the quarter came down to 1.69 per cent from 2.37 per cent as on March 31 this year. The figure was 6.31 per cent on June 30, 2003. Gross NPA declined to 8.03 per cent from 8.66 per cent on March 31, 2004. Singh said NPA was no longer an issue for Allahabad Bank.																								Deposits of the bank grew by 9.31 per cent against 0.99 per cent during the same period last year and on a year to year basis, it increased 33.81 per cent. This has been attributed to an increase in market share in aggregate deposits to 2.12 per cent. 																								The disbursement under retail lending during the quarter was Rs 352.03 crore against Rs 345.42 crore during the same period last year. To enhance the retail lending activities, the bank plans to open 100 new retail banking boutiques during the current fiscal. 																								Allahabad Bank also plans to utilise its wholly-owned subsidiary AllBank Finance for potential business activities based on the model of SBI Capital.Union Bank net up																								Union Bank of India has posted a 32.42 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 210.40 crore in the first quarter ended June 30, 2004, compared with Rs 158.88 crore in the previous corresponding period. 																								The companys total income rose to Rs 1,400.65 crore during the quarter under review against Rs 1,277.71 crore posted during the same period a year ago, Union Bank informed the Bombay Stock Exchange here today.
